\begin_layout Title
Inter-Party Avalanche Incidents May Increase Quadratically With Skier Density
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Charles Hagedorn
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
We estimate from first principles a common-sense result: When the density
 of backcountry travelers becomes comparable to the size of a day's potential
 avalanches, inter-party avalanche incidents will become a substantial fraction
 of all avalanche incidents.
 Furthermore, this model suggests that the likelihood of inter-party incidents
 is quadratic in the density of travelers â€“ twice as many parties quadruples
 the likelihood.
 The argument is made, with selected North American incidents from 2004-2019,
 that inter-party incidents are a timely concern.
 To spur conversation, we enumerate a variety of untested strategies to
 mitigate inter-party hazard.
\end_layout

