Weather and snow conditions as density and consequence amplifiers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Storm-skiing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is a guess, but the Pacific-Northwestern inter-party avalanche hazard
 may be at its greatest on deep-snow storm-skiing days, when trailbreaking
 is arduous, avalanches are likely, and powder fever is high.
 Arduous trailbreaking may be the most-powerful concentrator of backcountry
 travelers, amplifying the already-powerful magnetism of an extant skintrack.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On storm-skiing days, day-tripping backcountry skiers embark from a limited
 set of trailheads and head for a limited set of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

safe
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 objectives.
 In Western Washington State, with a population of thousands of active backcount
ry skiers
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "NWACAnnualReport2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, there are approximately nine such popular trailheads: Mount Baker, Stevens
 Pass, Yodelin, Alpental, Commonwealth Basin, Bullion Basin, Paradise, Hurricane
 Ridge, and White Pass.
 As skintracks are forged more-deeply into the morning, they bifurcate,
 but the number of traditional and natural ski options remains slim.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Optimal conditions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Good
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 conditions can concentrate parties.
 Mountains and routes offer only certain optimal times for passage.
 In the Cascades, and perhaps everywhere, this can be seen prominently in
 periods of spring/summer skiing; both snowpack and limited access curtail
 skiing at other times.
 There are narrow optimal windows for all of Tahoma/Rainier's Fuhrer Finger,
 the North Face of the Northwest Ridge of Pahto/Adams, and Ulrich's Couloirs
 of Stuart â€“ these are listed for their combination of popularity and constraine
d terrain, where a small summer slide can ravage anyone below.
 Indeed, on April 1, 2019, it was reported
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "HesserTetongBackup"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 that 15 parties attempted, and many bottlenecked, the ski route on the
 Grand Teton.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wintertime weather windows provide perhaps even more temporal concentration,
 as the number of good days for attempting bold routes is slim, perhaps
 only one or two weekends per season.
 Fortunately, for now, the number of skiers attempting bold winter routes
 seems low-enough that inter-party hazard is likely to be a smaller concern.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition to temporal concentration at the scale of days, safety and ski-quali
ty considerations may also concentrate skiers on shorter durations.
 Springtime daily melt-freeze/corn cycles can constrain safe skiing to time
 intervals measured in hours.
 The arrival of a storm or imminent warming can force travelers to enter
 or cross slopes before hazard increases.
 Finally, the perceived pressure from other people, whether to make the
 first tracks on a slope or, again paradoxically, to cross/descend a slope
 
\emph on
before
\emph default
 the presence of other skiers can make the slope more hazardous, can concentrate
 parties in small areas.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Reduced visibility
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If nearby parties cannot be seen, and the distances between parties are
 greater than that allowed by voice contact, it is impossible to be aware
 of anyone above or below.
 In low-visibility conditions in densely-skied areas, this may drive us
 to avoid skiing or ascending an otherwise-reasonable route simply because
 it may not be possible to verify that the route is free of other travelers.
\end_layout

