\begin_layout Section
Mitigation
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Mitigation"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is unlikely, and perhaps undesireable, that the number of backcountry
 travelers be reduced.
 Therefore, we must find ways to limit the likelihood of inter-party incidents.
 The following are strategies that may mitigate the risk.
 There are certainly more â€“ these are suggested to organize and catalyze
 discussion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Awareness and Education
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Awareness of the increasing likelihood of inter-party conflict with density
 may, on its own, help to curtail inter-party incidents.
 That is, of course, the intent of this work.
 In places where the density of skiers approaches the critical density,
 the hazard should be discussed and mitigated.
 At least a passing mention of inter-party hazard in avalanche education
 at all levels now seems prudent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As better understanding of the factors that lead to inter-party avalanche
 incidents becomes understood, it will make sense to bring light to the
 hazard in avalanche bulletins.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Density reduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The root of inter-party incidents is not the 
\emph on
number
\emph default
 of backcountry travelers, but their 
\emph on
density
\emph default
.
 Backcountry travelers use a tiny fraction of North American alpine terrain,
 perhaps primarily due to access constraints.
 Following the Kendall Peak accident
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "KendallDecember19"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, the author has sharply curtailed trips into densely-skied terrain, choosing
 lesser-known destinations, difficult access, or lower-quality snow in order
 to decrease overhead risk from other parties.
 While this strategy has limits, there are still lonely places with great
 skiing to be found on the map.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As advocacy organizations work to expand wintertime access, it may be reasonable
 to add safety to the reasons for improved access.
 Inferring from our estimates, it is natural to encourage party densities
 below one per characteristic-avalanche-size.
 D2 slides are roughly 0.01 km
\begin_inset Formula $^{2}$
\end_inset

 in area.
 D3 slides are roughly 0.1 km
\begin_inset Formula $^{2}$
\end_inset

 in area
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
