\begin_layout Subsection
Travel practices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If density cannot be wholly avoided, then we must find ways to limit our
 susceptibility to other parties and the risks we may pose to others.
 We cannot control others' choices, but we can control our own.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Defensive routefinding
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Like defensive driving, defensive routefinding consists of making choices
 that mitigate the risks that others may pose.
 Careful selection of routes through terrain, and, to a lesser extent, times
 to pass through terrain, can strongly limit the chance that another party's
 avalanche might hit us.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Examples: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Many ridgelines are not susceptible to slides from above â€“ travelling upon
 such a ridgeline inherently provides substantial protection from any inter-part
y incident.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Some routes pass through areas of unavoidable avalanche hazard â€“ there are
 plenty of examples: The Mousetrap
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "MousetrapAsulkanGuide"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 at Roger's Pass, Source Lake Basin and Mushroom Couloir at Snoqualmie Pass.
 Avoiding those areas during times that 
\emph on
human-triggered
\emph default
 slides are likely, rather than only when natural slides are likely, will
 limit the risk of an inter-party incident.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The Hawkins Mountain (Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Hawkins"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) and Turbo Hillclimb (Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
