\begin_layout Section
Conclusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have made a first-principles estimation of the scaling of inter-party
 avalanche incidents with party-density and found it to be quadratic.
 Furthermore, we find that inter-party incidents should become a significant
 fraction of avalanche incidents with the localized party density approaches
 one party per avalanche area.
 This result is independent of the day's likelihood of triggering avalanches.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We explored a series of North-American avalanche incidents in order to show
 varied ways in which inter-party incidents have occurred.
 Moreover, the party-densities at which these incidents occurred are roughly
 consistent with our model, with many incidents near 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{party}}A_{\text{avalanche}}\sim0.1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We enumerated and discussed a number of possible strategies for mitigating
 inter-party avalanche hazards.
 Improved awareness, spreading our parties out over greater area, travelling
 with others in mind, implementing regional travel standards, and communicating
 more-effectively may all help to limit the number of incidents.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As this work was first drafted in an autumn-2018 Seattle coffee shop, customers
 discussed how their friends encountered 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lines of cars
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 at a local hiking trailhead.
 This aligns with our experience in recent years, with unprecedented numbers
 of wilderness travelers at every trailhead and the disappearance of lonely
 places in the Cascades.
 Inter-party avalanche incidents are coming, if they have not already arrived.
 It behooves us, individually and as a community, to develop strategies
 to proactively address this emerging hazard.
\end_layout

